
[1]firkin

   FIRKIN, n. fur'kin.

   A measure of capacity, being the fourth part of a barrel. It is nine
   gallons of beer, or eight gallons of ale, soap or herrings. In America,
   the firkin is rarely used, except for butter or lard, and signifies a
   small vessel or cask of indeterminate size, or of different sizes,
   regulated by the statutes of the different states.
